text.Taxonomy and naming:
The species was first formally described by Ludwig Diels in 1905 and the description was published in Botanische Jahrbücher für Systematik, Pflanzengeschichte und Pflanzengeographie. The specific epithet (platythamnos) is derived from the Ancient Greek πλατύς (platús) meaning “flat”, "broad" or "wide" and θάμνος (thámnos) meaning "bush" or "shrub".There are 3 subspecies:

Eremophila platythamnos Diels subsp. platythamnos which has glabrous branches and leaves;
Eremophila platythamnos subsp. exotrachys (Kraenzl.)Chinnock which has hairy branches and leaves, and sepals that are two different sizes, with the inner pair longest;
Eremophila platythamnos subsp. villosa Chinnock which has hairy branches and leaves, and 5 equal-sized sepals;
